<subSubSection id="DDBD6569FFC8055089C3FC3AE18F10BD" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="951836E2FFC8055089C3FC3AE18F10BD" blockId="28.[151,1437,1017,2025]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">
<emphasis id="A7D3EAF0FFC8055089C3FC3AE47A1067" bold="true" box="[151,379,1017,1042]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Diagnosis (female).</emphasis>
Metallic purple species somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName id="52A74D61FFC805508A2FFC39E12E1064" authorityName="Fachin &amp; Hauser" authorityYear="2018" box="[891,1071,1018,1041]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Himantigera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amauroptera">
<emphasis id="A7D3EAF0FFC805508A2FFC39E12E1064" box="[891,1071,1018,1041]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">H. amauroptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but less dark. Upper frons only slightly narrower than widest margin of frontal callus, with lateral area at least twice width of medial area ventrally (
<figureCitation id="0D9C2A67FFC8055089CBFB82E5F5102F" box="[159,244,1089,1114]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1448,1471]" captionTargetBox="[196,1394,188,1425]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[196,1395,188,1425]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. Head in frontal view of Himantigera species. 13–16. H. nigrifemorata (13. Male, Mexico; 14. Female, Mexico; 15. Male, Costa Rica; 16. Female, Costa Rica). 17–18. H. silvestris (17. Male, paratype [CNC]; 18. Female). 19. H. superba, male. 20–21. H. amauroptera nov. sp., paratype (20. Male; 21. Female). 22. H. xanthopoda nov. sp., male holotype. 23. H. sp. A, female. 24. H. sp. B, male. Scale bar, 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614800/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
). Tarsomeres entirely white yellow, last two tarsomeres with dark pilosity. R 
<subScript id="092334A7FFC805508D37FB93E17A102B" attach="left" box="[1123,1147,1104,1118]" fontSize="6" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">2+3</subScript>
arising beyond r–m (
<figureCitation id="0D9C2A67FFC805508C3AFB82E5B710F5" captionStart="FIGURES 33–38" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1466,1489]" captionTargetBox="[164,1426,193,1456]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[163,1427,190,1457]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 33–38. Detail of vein R 2+3 in wings of Himantigera species. 33. H. nigrifemorata, male. 34. H. silvestris, male, paratype [CNC]. 35. H. superba, male. 36. H. amauroptera nov. sp., male paratype. 37. H. xanthopoda nov. sp., male paratype. 38. H. sp. A, female. Black arrow points R 2+3 vein. Scale bar, 0.5 mm. Abbreviation: R 2+3, second branch of radius." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614806/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
), but not as far as in 
<taxonomicName id="52A74D61FFC8055088C9FBAAE75110F5" authorityName="Fachin &amp; Hauser" authorityYear="2018" box="[413,592,1129,1152]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Himantigera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amauroptera">
<emphasis id="A7D3EAF0FFC8055088C9FBAAE75110F5" box="[413,592,1129,1152]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">H. amauroptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, only being at a distance equal to that of r–m, more similar to the state seen in 
<taxonomicName id="52A74D61FFC8055089E0FB4EE47010D1" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1847" box="[180,369,1164,1188]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Himantigera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrifemorata">
<emphasis id="A7D3EAF0FFC8055089E0FB4EE47010D1" box="[180,369,1164,1188]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">H. nigrifemorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Genital fork very wide posteriorly as seen in 
<taxonomicName id="52A74D61FFC805508A2EFB4EE12C10D1" authorityName="Fachin &amp; Hauser" authorityYear="2018" box="[890,1069,1165,1188]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Himantigera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amauroptera">
<emphasis id="A7D3EAF0FFC805508A2EFB4EE12C10D1" box="[890,1069,1165,1188]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">H. amauroptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but with its two posterior thirds almost equally wide, and with very short projections on the posterior margin (
<figureCitation id="0D9C2A67FFC805508AAAFB73E18010BD" box="[1022,1153,1200,1225]" captionStart="FIGURES 78–82" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1895,1918]" captionTargetBox="[283,1333,176,1778]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[150,1438,176,1891]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 78–82. 78–79. Himantigera amauroptera nov. sp., female paratype. 78. Female terminalia, dorsal view. 79. Genital fork, dorsal view. 80–82. Himantigera sp. A. 80. Genital fork, dorsal view. 81. Genital fork, lateral view. 82. Genital fork, ventral view. Abbreviations: cerc, cercus; go, genital opening; pb, posterior bridge; pp, posterolateral process; st, sternite; tg, tergite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614828/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Figs 80–82</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
